<TEXT type="str">Bafana Bafana assistant coach, Owen Da Gama,believes that for any coach, it would be an honour to coach the national team. 
 
Following Shakes Mashaba’s dismissal at the end of last year, the South African national team is currently coachless, with Roger Da Sa, Milutin Sredojevic, Gavin Hunt, Muhsin Ertugral, Carlos Queiroz, Hervé Renard and Pitso Mosimane rumoured to be shortlisted for the role. When asked about how a new coach could change the dynamics of the team, Da Gama said that it will depend on circumstances, before saying that he is also considering the next step for his own future. 
 
“It all depends on who the person is, coming in, and what the situation is. And, obviously, for myself as well, I’m a very experienced coach. I’ve gone over 54 matches with Bafana and over 30 matches with the under 23s,” he told Soccer Laduma. “That’s a lot of matches at national level and, for me, I can’t just be a journeyman, I can’t just be an assistant coach all the time. So, I’ve got to weigh up my options, see what the bosses say and then just take it from there.” 
 
